reason.tex:
%text If $y = f(x)$, then $x = f^{-1}(y)$ and not $\dfrac{1}{f(y)}$. And hence, %
\begin{align} (f\circ g)\left( x\right)&=y= 2x^3 + 7 \\ \implies (f\circ g)^{-1}(y)&=x=\sqrt[3]\dfrac{y-7}{2} \\ \end{align} \\
%text But \underline\text{the convention} is to write $x$ as the independent variable and $y$ as the dependent variable therefore, % \begin{align} (f\circ g)^{-1}(x) = \sqrt[3]\dfrac{x-7}{2} \end{align}
